<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Facebook on Linguista</title><link>https://linguista.cn/tags/facebook/</link><description>Recent content in Facebook on Linguista</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>zh-cn</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 10 Sep 2018 00:00:00 +0800</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://linguista.cn/tags/facebook/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>扎克伯格能在Facebook破坏民主之前修复它吗</title><link>https://linguista.cn/rosetta/technology/can-zuckerberg-fix-facebook-before-it-breaks-democracy/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Sep 2018 00:00:00 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://linguista.cn/rosetta/technology/can-zuckerberg-fix-facebook-before-it-breaks-democracy/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="扎克伯格能在facebook破坏民主之前修复它吗"&gt;扎克伯格能在Facebook破坏民主之前修复它吗&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2 id="摘要"&gt;摘要&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;本文是《纽约客》对Facebook创始人马克·扎克伯格的深度特写。在经历了两年持续不断的争议之后，记者走进扎克伯格位于帕洛阿尔托的家中，试图探究这位全球最知名的科技企业家如何面对Facebook对民主制度造成的威胁，以及他能否真正修复这个拥有数十亿用户的社交平台所带来的深层问题。&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="核心概念及解读"&gt;核心概念及解读&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Facebook与民主危机&lt;/strong&gt;：指Facebook平台上虚假信息传播、数据隐私泄露及算法操控等问题对民主选举和公共舆论造成的系统性威胁&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;扎克伯格的领导风格&lt;/strong&gt;：文章揭示其极强的竞争意识和执行力，同事形容他是一台无情的执行机器，善于从心理层面制定博弈策略&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;科技与心理学的交汇&lt;/strong&gt;：扎克伯格将Facebook定义为处于技术与心理学交叉点上的文化产品，这也是其争议的根源所在&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;硅谷隐私悖论&lt;/strong&gt;：扎克伯格一边倡导开放透明，一边花费数千万美元购买周边房产保护个人隐私，折射出科技领袖在公开与私密之间的深刻矛盾&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By Evan Osnos&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The New Yorker&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;64 min&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;September 10, 2018&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://newyorker.com/magazine/2018/09/17/can-mark-zuckerberg-fix-facebook-before-it-breaks-democracy?utm_source=pocket_shared"&gt;View Original&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://pocket-image-cache.com//filters:format%28jpg%29:extract_focal%28%29/https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fverso%2Fstatic%2Fthe-new-yorker%2Fassets%2Flogo.svg" alt=""&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At ten o’clock on a weekday morning in August, &lt;a href="https://www.newyorker.com/tag/mark-zuckerberg"&gt;Mark Zuckerberg,&lt;/a&gt; the chairman and C.E.O. of &lt;a href="https://www.newyorker.com/tag/facebook"&gt;Facebook&lt;/a&gt;, opened the front door of his house in Palo Alto, California, wearing the tight smile of obligation. He does not enjoy interviews, especially after two years of ceaseless controversy. Having got his start as a programmer with a nocturnal bent, he is also not a morning person. Walking toward the kitchen, which has a long farmhouse table and cabinets painted forest green, he said, “I haven’t eaten breakfast yet. Have you?”&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Google should pull an Android on Facebook</title><link>https://linguista.cn/person/naval/orig/google-should-pull-an-android-on-facebook/</link><pubDate>Thu, 07 Jul 2011 04:23:18 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://linguista.cn/person/naval/orig/google-should-pull-an-android-on-facebook/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://linguista.cn/person/naval/zh/google-should-pull-an-android-on-facebook.zh/"&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
